I wrote pro strats for pre-pre-production,

87
00:04:27,603 --> 00:04:29,685
which doesn't really quite roll off the tongue quite right.

88
00:04:29,705 --> 00:04:30,105
That's OK.

89
00:04:31,026 --> 00:04:33,488
These are things that help us vet an idea before we even

90
00:04:33,588 --> 00:04:35,850
start work on a prototype sometimes.

91
00:04:37,371 --> 00:04:39,213
The first one is called platonic scope.

92
00:04:39,593 --> 00:04:40,974
It's kind of a dorky name for a thing,

93
00:04:40,994 --> 00:04:42,496
but I want to explain what I mean real quick.

94
00:04:44,377 --> 00:04:47,560
There's this thing that you can think

95
00:04:47,600 --> 00:04:49,421
of as like a game production serveress,

96
00:04:49,441 --> 00:04:50,362
this three-headed thing.

97
00:04:50,402 --> 00:04:52,184
There's scope, and budget, and schedule.

98
00:04:54,200 --> 00:04:56,361
These are basically fancy abstractions

99
00:04:56,421 --> 00:04:58,062
for some pretty discrete resources

100
00:04:58,102 --> 00:04:59,663
that you have as a game maker.

101
00:05:00,363 --> 00:05:02,984
There's sort of game quality or whatever you're building

102
00:05:03,024 --> 00:05:04,225
and whatever you're trying to output.

103
00:05:04,245 --> 00:05:05,526
There's the money you have.

104
00:05:05,566 --> 00:05:06,847
There's the time that you have.

105
00:05:07,247 --> 00:05:08,968
And if you imagine these as kind of like three

106
00:05:09,008 --> 00:05:11,109
points of a triangle, different games

107
00:05:11,309 --> 00:05:13,310
are going to sort of have different triangles.

108
00:05:13,890 --> 00:05:16,472
And different game ideas react to changes in these variables

109
00:05:16,512 --> 00:05:16,952
differently.

110
00:05:17,352 --> 00:05:20,874
Increasing the budget or the amount of time

111
00:05:20,894 --> 00:05:22,675
that you have to build something may or may not

112
00:05:22,715 --> 00:05:22,975
affect.

113
00:05:24,096 --> 00:05:29,041
The ship date, or the budget, or the output quality, since we're trying to make games

114
00:05:29,201 --> 00:05:34,185
commercially and somehow also eat food, time and money obviously matter a lot.

115
00:05:35,446 --> 00:05:37,068
But this quality question is kind of weird.

116
00:05:38,882 --> 00:05:42,563
There's this sort of philosophical notion of the Platonic ideal.

117
00:05:43,563 --> 00:05:47,945
This is something that is like the most perfect or true version of itself.

118
00:05:48,105 --> 00:05:49,786
It's somehow perfectly authentic.

119
00:05:49,866 --> 00:05:51,326
It's an er-thing.

120
00:05:51,346 --> 00:05:55,868
It is like its perfect essence or whatever.

121
00:05:56,866 --> 00:05:59,790
our target for this quality thing that we're trying to

122
00:05:59,830 --> 00:06:03,394
achieve, I think, is to somehow create the platonic version of

123
00:06:03,555 --> 00:06:07,680
any given game idea. So this is weird because it's radically

124
00:06:07,720 --> 00:06:10,643
different from game to game. The ideal sandbox game is going to

125
00:06:10,663 --> 00:06:12,346
be really different from the ideal RPG.

126
00:06:15,335 --> 00:06:17,576
And it's also totally impossible to actually do.

127
00:06:17,956 --> 00:06:20,097
Nobody's actually going to achieve this or pull this off.

128
00:06:21,077 --> 00:06:24,518
But I think it's still useful as sort of a target,

129
00:06:24,538 --> 00:06:25,599
or something to aim at, or something

130
00:06:25,619 --> 00:06:28,280
to think about when we're trying to kind of balance quality

131
00:06:28,900 --> 00:06:30,401
and money and time.

132
00:06:30,741 --> 00:06:31,741
So I have these three variables.

133
00:06:33,302 --> 00:06:36,763
Usually for us, time and money have kind of an upper boundary.

134
00:06:39,033 --> 00:06:40,994
And then we have this sort of like,

135
00:06:42,195 --> 00:06:45,216
what is the best version of any particular game

136
00:06:45,516 --> 00:06:46,557
according to its own rules?

137
00:06:47,177 --> 00:06:50,419
What is the platonic ideal of that particular game idea?

138
00:06:51,660 --> 00:06:54,381
And so the first way that we try to manage risk

139
00:06:54,421 --> 00:06:56,522
when we're in the early stages of trying to decide

140
00:06:56,542 --> 00:06:58,663
what to work on next is to just ask this question.

141
00:06:59,104 --> 00:07:01,505
Given the time and money that we have access to,

142
00:07:02,085 --> 00:07:04,186
which of our game ideas can we get the closest

143
00:07:04,386 --> 00:07:06,207
to its platonic ideal?

144
00:07:07,804 --> 00:07:09,065
This is a really insane question.

145
00:07:09,085 --> 00:07:10,626
There's so many things going on.

146
00:07:11,507 --> 00:07:12,708
We may not have a prototype yet.

147
00:07:14,649 --> 00:07:17,532
Even if you do have a prototype, the kind of games

148
00:07:17,552 --> 00:07:19,093
that we build and the reason that we build them

149
00:07:19,153 --> 00:07:21,354
is they tend to grow in really unpredictable ways.

150
00:07:21,855 --> 00:07:22,936
We think that's a good thing.

151
00:07:23,836 --> 00:07:26,718
But you can grow a really big tree from a really small seed

152
00:07:26,738 --> 00:07:27,219
sometimes.

153
00:07:27,299 --> 00:07:29,821
So how do you even guess which of these game ideas

154
00:07:30,341 --> 00:07:33,343
we can actually get the closest to this desired output quality?

155
00:07:34,524 --> 00:07:36,266
Predicting absolutes is really hard.

156
00:07:37,557 --> 00:07:42,601
uh, accuracy in predicting the exact budget and dev time and design complexity and the

157
00:07:42,661 --> 00:07:47,164
final output quality of an original game idea is impossible, but I think you can kind of

158
00:07:47,184 --> 00:07:52,108
make a relative comparison. You can pit a handful of ideas against each other, you can

159
00:07:52,148 --> 00:07:56,031
imagine which one can take you farthest given the resources you have, and that might actually

160
00:07:56,091 --> 00:07:56,232
help.

161
00:07:57,583 --> 00:07:58,944
So that's where that dorky name comes from.

162
00:07:59,284 --> 00:08:02,125
You may be able to make a pretty good call about which

163
00:08:02,145 --> 00:08:04,186
of your game ideas you can take the farthest, given

164
00:08:04,226 --> 00:08:05,347
the resources that you have.

165
00:08:06,247 --> 00:08:07,888
And this isn't the end all, be all of green lighting.

166
00:08:07,908 --> 00:08:10,929
It's kind of just sort of one of our first steps that we like.

167
00:08:12,850 --> 00:08:16,291
The next one is the inverse pyramid test, which I think

168
00:08:16,311 --> 00:08:17,211
sounds kind of ominous.

169
00:08:17,411 --> 00:08:20,793
But inverted pyramid is this kind of nice shape

170
00:08:21,633 --> 00:08:24,714
because it maintains the same overall profile over time

171
00:08:25,214 --> 00:08:26,215
as you add new layers.

172
00:08:29,474 --> 00:08:34,258
I think games that have this shape can decrease risk over time because you can stop prototyping

173
00:08:34,798 --> 00:08:38,861
at any point and you have a game that has all the properties of the thing that you're

174
00:08:38,881 --> 00:08:39,461
trying to achieve.

175
00:08:40,982 --> 00:08:45,306
If you have vertical strata or you have a regular crappy pyramid, it doesn't really

176
00:08:45,326 --> 00:08:47,347
have the same weird shape maintaining property.

177
00:08:49,136 --> 00:08:54,257
These shapes, I think, are really obviously inherently incomplete or unstable until you

178
00:08:54,298 --> 00:08:55,638
get all the final touches done.

179
00:08:56,398 --> 00:08:57,299
So why does this matter?

180
00:08:58,119 --> 00:09:01,680
Sometimes budget and schedule estimates end up being slightly off.

181
00:09:03,481 --> 00:09:10,304
So if you end up not having as much time and money as you were hoping, somehow, do you

182
00:09:10,344 --> 00:09:10,924
want to end up...

183
00:09:12,272 --> 00:09:13,352
with game like this?

184
00:09:15,673 --> 00:09:17,413
Or do you want a game that looks more like this?

