00:09:29,355 --> 00:09:33,216
it's intelligent, but you can't use skateboard wheels

190
00:09:33,576 --> 00:09:33,996
on a bike.

191
00:09:34,676 --> 00:09:37,217
So you have to revisit the whole notion of wheels

192
00:09:37,297 --> 00:09:38,557
each time you do this next step.

193
00:09:38,597 --> 00:09:40,438
You have to question your old assumptions.

194
00:09:41,902 --> 00:09:44,122
which I think is a nice touch when you're trying to sum

195
00:09:44,142 --> 00:09:44,942
something up like this.

196
00:09:45,463 --> 00:09:48,323
Not every idea is going to be a good fit for this model, right?

197
00:09:48,984 --> 00:09:50,084
But this is kind of our whole point.

198
00:09:50,184 --> 00:09:53,005
These pregame considerations that we're talking about

199
00:09:53,085 --> 00:09:54,545
are not best practices.

200
00:09:54,585 --> 00:09:56,426
We're not talking about design methodologies.

201
00:09:56,766 --> 00:09:58,846
We're not talking about workflow processes.

202
00:09:59,386 --> 00:10:02,747
These are ways of interrogating or examining

203
00:10:02,787 --> 00:10:04,328
an idea or a concept that you have.

204
00:10:05,877 --> 00:10:13,141
For us, the inverse pyramid test usually means that we end up focusing on systems-based games as opposed to content-based games.

205
00:10:13,822 --> 00:10:18,124
So a game with a lot of randomly generated content might be a pretty good fit for us.

206
00:10:18,244 --> 00:10:20,065
It takes a long time to nail down the basics,

207
00:10:21,366 --> 00:10:21,546
but

208
00:10:22,606 --> 00:10:24,347
when you're done with that step, you have a good game

209
00:10:24,367 --> 00:10:28,749
that's just very small. And then you just have to sort of add new things to it, and as you do that, it

210
00:10:29,010 --> 00:10:31,371
tends to grow in a kind of an exponential way.

211
00:10:32,772 --> 00:10:35,014
Sandbox games tend to have this property also.

212
00:10:35,034 --> 00:10:40,199
I think this is, you end up in situations

213
00:10:40,219 --> 00:10:41,780
where you can add one thing, and it actually

214
00:10:41,840 --> 00:10:45,023
doubles the size of the game or the expressive space

215
00:10:45,063 --> 00:10:45,504
of the game.

216
00:10:45,924 --> 00:10:48,726
And I think sandbox games being expressive,

217
00:10:48,746 --> 00:10:51,249
but sandbox games also having this property of,

218
00:10:51,769 --> 00:10:53,451
oh, we didn't get everything in that we wanted,

219
00:10:53,551 --> 00:10:55,472
but it's still a functioning thing,

220
00:10:55,532 --> 00:10:57,134
is one reason that they're so popular right now.

221
00:10:58,609 --> 00:11:00,091
There's a weird thing about the shape of game too,

222
00:11:00,111 --> 00:11:02,452
which is new layers and mechanics as you go up

223
00:11:02,552 --> 00:11:05,915
might be adding disproportionate amounts of new content.

224
00:11:06,275 --> 00:11:08,817
Because this isn't really just a triangle.

225
00:11:08,857 --> 00:11:11,659
This is like a multi-dimensional sort of prism

226
00:11:11,699 --> 00:11:13,180
that you're building as you build your game.

227
00:11:13,580 --> 00:11:15,441
And each new layer can add a lot,

228
00:11:15,522 --> 00:11:17,883
and it can alter and augment the existing layers.

229
00:11:20,625 --> 00:11:21,706
So we're talking about,

230
00:11:21,746 --> 00:11:23,087
when we're thinking about inverse pyramid

231
00:11:23,227 --> 00:11:24,848
or trying to think about minimum viable product,

232
00:11:24,868 --> 00:11:26,409
those are a bunch of the things that are on our mind

233
00:11:26,429 --> 00:11:27,570
when we're looking at game ideas.

234
00:11:29,001 --> 00:11:32,949
The next thing is the notion of taking creative risks,

235
00:11:33,290 --> 00:11:35,895
or another way to think about it is taking as many risks

236
00:11:36,015 --> 00:11:37,859
as possible without producing something

237
00:11:38,240 --> 00:11:40,104
that is completely alienating to people.

238
00:11:41,733 --> 00:11:42,993
to a commercial audience, right?

239
00:11:43,834 --> 00:11:44,674
And why even bother?

240
00:11:44,834 --> 00:11:47,656
So one reason to take creative risks

241
00:11:47,736 --> 00:11:49,817
is this may be why you went indie in the first place.

242
00:11:50,998 --> 00:11:53,299
It might be that nobody's making the game that you want to make.

243
00:11:54,340 --> 00:11:56,841
You notice that there's a gap that needs to be filled,

244
00:11:57,001 --> 00:11:58,782
or there's wilderness that needs to be explored.

245
00:11:59,223 --> 00:12:00,683
It's fun and feels really good.

246
00:12:02,264 --> 00:12:06,006
But it also is going to help your game differentiate itself

247
00:12:06,326 --> 00:12:08,007
from other games that are on the market right now.

248
00:12:09,509 --> 00:12:12,532
And this is kind of an apparent contradiction of commercial game making in a lot of ways.

249
00:12:14,154 --> 00:12:18,719
We are trying to make a game that looks like a commercial product that people want to exchange

250
00:12:18,799 --> 00:12:26,307
money for, but for practical reasons and for personal reasons, we need it to be somehow

251
00:12:26,427 --> 00:12:29,090
unique and to be new and to be original.

252
00:12:30,210 --> 00:12:31,450
to have a kind of a unique silhouette.

253
00:12:32,030 --> 00:12:36,112
And like, if you've ever done contract work or something

254
00:12:36,132 --> 00:12:38,312
and somebody sends you like an email, and they're like,

255
00:12:38,332 --> 00:12:41,654
hey, I want something really classic, but timeless,

256
00:12:42,114 --> 00:12:42,634
but modern.

257
00:12:43,074 --> 00:12:44,454
Like, that's the thing that we're dealing with, right?

258
00:12:44,474 --> 00:12:44,995
So.

259
00:12:47,806 --> 00:12:50,727
we're trying to make a game that's not unbuyable.

260
00:12:50,867 --> 00:12:53,849
So what is this idea of buyable?

261
00:12:53,889 --> 00:12:54,709
What's a buyable game?

262
00:12:54,729 --> 00:12:55,469
What does that even mean?

263
00:12:55,489 --> 00:12:56,710
And I think there are different ways

264
00:12:56,750 --> 00:12:58,291
of thinking about that and defining that.

265
00:12:58,411 --> 00:13:01,752
But how big a game is it?

266
00:13:02,072 --> 00:13:03,053
How accessible is it?

267
00:13:03,433 --> 00:13:06,494
How sort of fair is it?

268
00:13:06,594 --> 00:13:10,256
Is it an exciting power fantasy, or is this

269
00:13:10,296 --> 00:13:11,977
like a brutal, inaccessible thing?

270
00:13:14,104 --> 00:13:17,505
how deep do you have to dig to get to the interesting stuff versus how much of it has

271
00:13:17,545 --> 00:13:19,726
been kind of presented to you by the designer.

272
00:13:22,348 --> 00:13:25,630
The thing is, breaking some of these rules I think is a really great way to differentiate

273
00:13:25,650 --> 00:13:25,990
your game.

274
00:13:27,826 --> 00:13:30,208
And it's a way of kind of resolving this tension between

275
00:13:30,629 --> 00:13:32,811
making sort of a commercial product and making something

276
00:13:32,851 --> 00:13:33,892
original at the same time.

277
00:13:34,933 --> 00:13:36,414
So do you guys know this game, Minecraft?

278
00:13:37,275 --> 00:13:38,776
It's been pretty hot lately.

279
00:13:40,438 --> 00:13:43,120
I don't think it's actually a particularly accessible game.

280
00:13:43,161 --> 00:13:45,863
I don't think it's actually that much of a polished game.

281
00:13:45,883 --> 00:13:47,465
I think it actually breaks a bunch of these rules.

282
00:13:48,065 --> 00:13:51,068
But if you go back to this list, the how much game is

283
00:13:51,088 --> 00:13:51,508
their part?

284
00:13:51,869 --> 00:13:53,271
It's really, really, really good at that.

285
00:13:54,733 --> 00:13:56,415
Gone Home is a pretty short game.

286
00:13:56,435 --> 00:13:59,740
There's not a lot of game there in a classic, traditional sense.

287
00:14:00,100 --> 00:14:02,564
It's very polished. It's pretty accessible.

288
00:14:02,864 --> 00:14:06,990
It's about stories and themes that are new and have a kind of a broad audience.

289
00:14:09,243 --> 00:14:14,007
And I don't think any of these games really follow all the normal, viable formulation for a game.

290
00:14:15,508 --> 00:14:19,331
And I admire the way that these games take some progressive or challenging ideas

291
00:14:19,771 --> 00:14:25,076
and they find a way to sort of somehow still fit them just enough into this commercial game box

292
00:14:25,396 --> 00:14:28,338
to find a big audience and to support those developers doing their stuff.

293
00:14:29,479 --> 00:14:33,182
And there are lots of games that do follow all the rules, and they're still really neat games.

294
00:14:35,257 --> 00:14:39,700
These games, though, tend to be differentiated by just raw

295
00:14:40,040 --> 00:14:44,744
quality, or raw superficial quality, even.

296
00:14:46,445 --> 00:14:47,886
They're very long games.

297
00:14:47,906 --> 00:14:49,187
They're very large games.

298
00:14:49,207 --> 00:14:51,969
They have very beautiful graphics that you can see and

299
00:14:52,009 --> 00:14:52,850
notice immediately.

300
00:14:52,870 --> 00:14:56,193
This game, the Bloodborne game, is pretty good, right?

301
00:14:58,586 --> 00:15:05,631
So these games in some ways I think are taking fewer creative risks, but they're actually a lot riskier to do as a commercial venture.

302
00:15:05,931 --> 00:15:08,072
They have to have extremely good content.

303
00:15:08,793 --> 00:15:11,255
They tend to be really expensive to produce.

304
00:15:12,696 --> 00:15:16,478
You know, if The Witness had puzzles that were just bad,

305
00:15:17,459 --> 00:15:20,441
like, that's not a thing that can support itself anymore suddenly.

306
00:15:22,128 --> 00:15:25,037
So there's a lot of kind of internal pressure there that you have to handle.

307
00:15:25,458 --> 00:15:28,908
And I think it's easier for small devs to differentiate by breaking some of these rules.

308
00:15:30,872 --> 00:15:34,194
So another way of looking at this is the idea that you can't make everyone happy all the time.

309
00:15:35,135 --> 00:15:40,157
Which we've all heard a million times, we understand this on a cognitive level, on an emotional level.

310
00:15:40,798 --> 00:15:44,560
But when you're making art and you're trying to share it with the world, there's lots of tension or pressure

311
00:15:44,940 --> 00:15:47,121
to make concessions to reach out to new audiences.

312
00:15:47,541 --> 00:15:52,384
To draw in people who might not know about the thing that you're making, but you think that they'll totally love it.

313
00:15:52,944 --> 00:15:55,486
And if you're not careful, it's really easy to kind of...

314
00:15:56,646 --> 00:16:01,490
sort of stair-step your way into suddenly trying to design for all audiences,

315
00:16:01,550 --> 00:16:03,911
even though you knew at the start that that was kind of a bad idea.

316
00:16:03,951 --> 00:16:06,753
And I think when you do this, you're kind of undermining

317
00:16:07,334 --> 00:16:10,476
the things that made your game so interesting and so different in the first place.

318
00:16:11,077 --> 00:16:14,259
You know, if you tack on a crafting system or an RPG system,

319
00:16:14,719 --> 00:16:19,302
and you're starting to dilute the thing that maybe got people's attention in the first place.

320
00:16:20,296 --> 00:16:23,378
So creative risks, feels good, helps you stand out.

321
00:16:24,639 --> 00:16:25,519
It's a tricky balance, though.

322
00:16:25,539 --> 00:16:27,760
You have to have a lot of confidence and humility

323
00:16:27,780 --> 00:16:28,501
at the same time.

324
00:16:28,561 --> 00:16:29,201
It's not easy.

325
00:16:29,602 --> 00:16:30,982
I think it's totally worth it, though.

326
00:16:33,364 --> 00:16:36,165
Last but not least, the final thing

327
00:16:36,185 --> 00:16:40,668
is something that we call exposure design, which

328
00:16:41,368 --> 00:16:42,149
is basically this.

329
00:16:44,516 --> 00:16:46,317
And it's not a thing that you do or don't do.

330
00:16:46,598 --> 00:16:47,899
Marketing sort of just is.

331
00:16:47,959 --> 00:16:50,621
It's the part of your game that people can see or hear about.

332
00:16:51,454 --> 00:16:53,315
The first time someone sees a screenshot of your game

333
00:16:53,375 --> 00:16:55,757
is kind of also the first time they experience your game.

334
00:16:56,177 --> 00:16:57,898
And I think those first impressions matter a lot.

335
00:16:58,458 --> 00:17:00,339
Some things that are marketing.

336
00:17:01,680 --> 00:17:04,381
Let's play, seeing it on someone's phone on the bus.

337
00:17:04,621 --> 00:17:06,322
You saw a cool screenshot on Tumblr.

338
00:17:06,342 --> 00:17:08,503
You're looking at the loading screen,

339
00:17:08,523 --> 00:17:10,404
waiting for the game to actually start eventually.

340
00:17:10,824 --> 00:17:12,565
Somebody was just shouting at you last night

341
00:17:12,585 --> 00:17:13,626
about how cool it was.

342
00:17:14,747 --> 00:17:17,308
So if your project or your game is an iceberg,

343
00:17:17,328 --> 00:17:19,569
I kind of think of marketing as the 10% that

344
00:17:19,609 --> 00:17:20,450
sticks up out of the water.

345
00:17:21,712 --> 00:17:22,773
And that's called exposure.

346
00:17:24,794 --> 00:17:28,576
So marketing to us is basically exposure design.

347
00:17:28,836 --> 00:17:31,338
And I think it's really, really, really important.

348
00:17:31,778 --> 00:17:34,240
It's the only way that people get into the strange world

349
00:17:34,260 --> 00:17:35,520
that you put inside your game.

350
00:17:36,821 --> 00:17:39,182
And for us, exposure design is the idea

351
00:17:39,202 --> 00:17:41,884
that you can and should pay a lot of attention

352
00:17:41,924 --> 00:17:43,845
to designing that little top piece.

353
00:17:45,377 --> 00:17:50,020
Because it bears a huge design burden. It's kind of a gate into your game. It's often

354
00:17:50,040 --> 00:17:55,824
it's kind of a teacher. It needs to sort of be tempting. In some ways it's sort of like

355
00:17:55,864 --> 00:18:01,628
a restaurant menu. It's kind of this, it's the outer layer of this weird psychic playground

356
00:18:01,669 --> 00:18:04,010
thing that you built and that you're trying to share with other people.

357
00:18:05,275 --> 00:18:07,497
And it's a fundamental part of building a commercial game.

358
00:18:08,538 --> 00:18:10,119
And it's not a question that you can answer

359
00:18:10,180 --> 00:18:11,761
before you've started working on the game,

360
00:18:13,242 --> 00:18:15,824
any more than you can sit down and write a full game design

361
00:18:15,844 --> 00:18:18,326
document without even starting your prototype, right?

362
00:18:19,788 --> 00:18:24,572
Building original games tends to be the process of designing

363
00:18:24,612 --> 00:18:25,633
them and vice versa.

364
00:18:26,033 --> 00:18:27,654
But you can still think about this

365
00:18:27,774 --> 00:18:28,775
starting really, really early.

366
00:18:30,750 --> 00:18:33,773
So these are kind of within this way of interrogating

367
00:18:33,813 --> 00:18:35,915
our early game ideas or early prototype ideas.

368
00:18:36,355 --> 00:18:39,618
We also can sort of interrogate our marketing ideas.

369
00:18:41,020 --> 00:18:42,741
Does the 10% that's sticking out of the water

370
00:18:42,841 --> 00:18:45,584
communicate some of the qualities

371
00:18:45,744 --> 00:18:50,989
that make the game fit into that kind of marketing box?

372
00:18:52,370 --> 00:18:53,631
Does it also communicate?

373
00:18:54,038 --> 00:18:57,561
the part where you broke the rules and you did things that don't normally fit in the box and

374
00:18:57,581 --> 00:19:01,904
that make it stand out and make it seem different. And does it say that clearly and

375
00:19:01,924 --> 00:19:06,087
efficiently to the people who are going to like those things that you put into your

376
00:19:06,167 --> 00:19:13,333
iceberg? It's really difficult. It's also really, really easy to test. Um...

377
00:19:15,790 --> 00:19:20,332
I've, on a lot of previous games that we've worked on, we've been able to come up with a pitch,

378
00:19:20,372 --> 00:19:24,175
decide like, oh, these are the magic words, this is the elevator pitch, this is the screenshot we need to show,

379
00:19:24,255 --> 00:19:26,816
show it to people, and if they don't care, then you're doing it wrong.

380
00:19:26,836 --> 00:19:28,577
And you just go back and try again.

381
00:19:30,828 --> 00:19:32,109
So that part of it is kind of nice.

382
00:19:32,569 --> 00:19:33,750
There's a lot of trial and error,

383
00:19:33,830 --> 00:19:35,991
but at least you can get really clear feedback really,

384
00:19:36,031 --> 00:19:36,571
really easily.

385
00:19:36,591 --> 00:19:39,373
The other thing that's weird is it's not about explaining

386
00:19:39,413 --> 00:19:40,573
the whole game in five seconds.

387
00:19:40,613 --> 00:19:41,494
It's way weirder than that.

388
00:19:41,514 --> 00:19:43,255
You're trying to communicate some kind

389
00:19:43,295 --> 00:19:46,316
of essential experience and not just game mechanics.

390
00:19:48,037 --> 00:19:49,158
So there's a reason that this list

391
00:19:49,198 --> 00:19:51,899
doesn't include over-explaining everything that your game does

392
00:19:51,939 --> 00:19:52,400
all the time.

393
00:19:54,818 --> 00:19:59,641
And because you are trying to communicate this essential experience, not just mechanics or story,

394
00:20:01,122 --> 00:20:05,765
the way that you design the exposure, the way that you do your marketing,

395
00:20:06,205 --> 00:20:09,407
is going to vary enormously from project to project.

396
00:20:10,984 --> 00:20:16,789
And differentiation in exposure design or marketing has even more pressure because they

397
00:20:16,809 --> 00:20:18,630
don't even get to spend time with the whole game yet.

398
00:20:18,671 --> 00:20:21,293
They just have this little piece at the top that they're trying to check out.

399
00:20:21,773 --> 00:20:25,797
So what's going to make someone's eyes or ears or brain kind of stop and rest on that

400
00:20:25,897 --> 00:20:27,718
point before moving on to the next thing?

401
00:20:28,159 --> 00:20:33,883
What's going to sort of engender desire in them to talk about the little bit that they

402
00:20:33,943 --> 00:20:35,825
saw and to share it with their friends?

403
00:20:37,674 --> 00:20:41,197
This sounds really dramatic, but in a world of infinite icebergs, what makes yours so

404
00:20:41,258 --> 00:20:41,598
special?

405
00:20:41,958 --> 00:20:46,923
Whatever that quality is, can you tell by looking at that little top piece?

406
00:20:48,676 --> 00:20:50,397
And it's really tempting to think things like, well,

407
00:20:50,417 --> 00:20:51,838
the game is going to speak for itself,

408
00:20:52,138 --> 00:20:54,059
or I told lots of people about it.

409
00:20:54,180 --> 00:20:56,321
I already posted about it on Twitter twice.

410
00:20:56,961 --> 00:20:58,422
So we're pretty much fine.

411
00:21:00,303 --> 00:21:02,325
And in indie games for a while, we've

412
00:21:02,345 --> 00:21:05,647
been talking about this idea of the Chang infinity hypothesis,

413
00:21:06,828 --> 00:21:09,469
which is named after Jamie Chang from Clay, who's

414
00:21:09,489 --> 00:21:10,670
been a big inspiration for us.

415
00:21:11,090 --> 00:21:12,812
It's sort of the notion that there are always

416
00:21:13,172 --> 00:21:15,974
more people out there who want to know about the thing

417
00:21:15,994 --> 00:21:16,414
that you made.

418
00:21:17,614 --> 00:21:20,936
And Tom Francis, who's a former game journalist and now game designer,

419
00:21:22,197 --> 00:21:28,440
made a game called Gunpoint a little while ago that was, by all accounts, a pretty great, successful indie game.

420
00:21:28,880 --> 00:21:33,762
And he went and crunched the numbers and found that if you round to the closest integer,

421
00:21:34,443 --> 00:21:36,644
0% of Steam users own a copy of Gunpoint.

422
00:21:38,893 --> 00:21:40,233
And he still sold more than enough

423
00:21:40,253 --> 00:21:42,794
to fund his entire current project, which

424
00:21:42,834 --> 00:21:43,655
is looking really good.

425
00:21:43,935 --> 00:21:47,436
Anyway, I think it's really tempting to think of marketing

426
00:21:47,636 --> 00:21:49,597
as something that you do later, as something

427
00:21:49,617 --> 00:21:51,398
that you do external to your game.

428
00:21:51,858 --> 00:21:53,619
And instead, I think you have to,

429
00:21:55,219 --> 00:21:56,900
it's not even whether or not you want to do this.

430
00:21:57,020 --> 00:21:59,041
Whether you like it or not, marketing

431
00:21:59,121 --> 00:22:02,242
is a very integral and natural part of your game design.

432
00:22:04,357 --> 00:22:08,100
So yeah, so these are kind of our main pregame considerations

433
00:22:08,200 --> 00:22:10,842
when we are greenlighting projects at Fingy.

434
00:22:12,163 --> 00:22:13,784
We try to think about how good can we

435
00:22:13,824 --> 00:22:17,027
get this idea with the resources that we have access to.

436
00:22:17,827 --> 00:22:20,429
What happens if we run out of time or money?

437
00:22:20,589 --> 00:22:21,950
Is the project going to be salvageable,

438
00:22:22,070 --> 00:22:25,213
or is it going to be kind of time to start scrambling?

439
00:22:26,614 --> 00:22:27,835
Is this an idea that we?

440
00:22:29,296 --> 00:22:32,721
that we personally are passionate about and that we think will stand out

441
00:22:32,841 --> 00:22:34,924
because it's so different from everything else that's out there

442
00:22:35,445 --> 00:22:41,293
and how hard are we going to have to work to be able to expose those special qualities

443
00:22:41,754 --> 00:22:44,859
to people who have never played this before and have no idea what it is.

444
00:22:46,991 --> 00:22:50,152
And kind of as a counterpoint, so I had all these games up here

445
00:22:50,192 --> 00:22:52,713
before because I think they take really

446
00:22:52,773 --> 00:22:53,973
interesting creative risks.

447
00:22:56,414 --> 00:22:59,275
FMV games were not a super hot genre up until pretty recently.

448
00:23:00,316 --> 00:23:01,256
These games are expressive.

449
00:23:01,296 --> 00:23:01,956
They're beautiful.

450
00:23:02,116 --> 00:23:02,697
They're smart.

451
00:23:03,837 --> 00:23:05,438
They're also really bad fits for the way

452
00:23:05,478 --> 00:23:06,958
that we actually make games.

453
00:23:07,478 --> 00:23:09,099
I probably wouldn't green light these projects

454
00:23:09,159 --> 00:23:10,800
because I don't know how to manage their scope.

455
00:23:11,300 --> 00:23:12,140
I don't know what to do.

456
00:23:13,020 --> 00:23:15,242
if their budget was running low partway through.

457
00:23:16,563 --> 00:23:19,404
But I think these games are very good fits for the people that

458
00:23:19,464 --> 00:23:20,285
actually made them.

459
00:23:21,246 --> 00:23:22,927
These are games that were playing

460
00:23:23,047 --> 00:23:28,050
to the strengths of those teams in a really powerful way.

461
00:23:29,471 --> 00:23:35,356
This is a recent example of a game that I think is really smart, and this is the kind

462
00:23:35,376 --> 00:23:40,460
of thing that I feel like I understand pretty well, and I think that we would have probably

463
00:23:40,500 --> 00:23:41,882
greenlit and gone forward with.

464
00:23:42,382 --> 00:23:43,623
It's called Double Daggers.

465
00:23:44,284 --> 00:23:46,465
It doesn't have a whole lot of moving parts.

466
00:23:47,606 --> 00:23:50,528
if they decide to expand it later by adding a new piece.

467
00:23:51,568 --> 00:23:52,809
The core game is still there.

468
00:23:52,869 --> 00:23:55,511
The new piece isn't going to change the overall shape

469
00:23:55,531 --> 00:23:59,373
of that, but it may potentially make it bigger, deeper, more

470
00:23:59,413 --> 00:24:01,054
complex, more interesting in the future.

471
00:24:02,795 --> 00:24:03,595
It breaks some rules.

472
00:24:03,915 --> 00:24:06,737
It's a 3D FPS that just doesn't have any levels at all.

473
00:24:08,758 --> 00:24:11,459
And I think the screenshots have a pretty clear identity.

474
00:24:11,820 --> 00:24:14,641
And they do a pretty good job of showing most

475
00:24:14,681 --> 00:24:15,662
of what you do in this game.

476
00:24:15,682 --> 00:24:15,962
And that's it.

477
00:24:16,837 --> 00:24:22,559
pretty much you'd shoot orange finger lasers at skulls. That's, that's everything. That's

478
00:24:22,599 --> 00:24:27,481
the whole game. They boxed it up. Um, so does this mean that all arena shooters are a really

479
00:24:27,521 --> 00:24:32,524
good idea? No. Uh, but the mix of ingredients and ideas for this particular thing I think

480
00:24:32,584 --> 00:24:33,504
is really intelligent.

481
00:24:35,409 --> 00:24:38,551
So it may not even be that important that you follow all

482
00:24:38,571 --> 00:24:40,052
of our rules or whatever, right?

483
00:24:40,912 --> 00:24:44,735
Instead, you can start to think about what

484
00:24:44,775 --> 00:24:45,855
do these mean for you?

485
00:24:46,016 --> 00:24:47,457
What do they mean for your background?

486
00:24:47,477 --> 00:24:48,797
What do they mean for your skills?

487
00:24:48,817 --> 00:24:50,258
What do they mean for your audience?

488
00:24:50,699 --> 00:24:52,460
What do they mean for your creative needs?

489
00:24:53,501 --> 00:24:58,304
And even more broadly, just think about anything,

490
00:24:59,104 --> 00:24:59,605
kind of, ever.

491
00:25:02,892 --> 00:25:05,653
We've had this experience over and over and over in the last year where somebody runs

492
00:25:05,693 --> 00:25:09,814
up and they say, hey, just quit our job, invest our life savings in this thing.

